        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "A1",
      "title": "Was/were: Use",
      "slug": "a1-waswere-use",
      "order": 13,
      "chapter": "Past tenses",
      "description": "Was/were are the past forms of am/is/are. Present: am/is = past: was. Present: are = past: were. I‘m happy. ⇒ I was happy. (am ⇒ was) She is at her office. ⇒ She was at her office. (is ⇒ was) You are late. ⇒ You were late. (are ⇒ were) We use was/were to talk about the past. We often use past expressions of time: yesterday, last night, last week, two months ago, etc. She was in Stuttgart last summer. We were late to the party last night. We use was/were in the expression was/were born. The expression be born is always past (NOT present): was/were born. ‘Where were you born?’ ‘I was born in Sweden.’ ‘Where are you born?’ ‘I am born in Sweden.’ Mozart was born in 1756.",
      "analogy": "",
      "real_world_use": "",
      "memory_hook": "",
      "icon": "📚",
      "rules": []
    },
    {
      "level": "A1",
      "title": "Past simple regular",
      "slug": "a1-past-simple-regular",
      "order": 14,
      "chapter": "Past tenses",
      "description": "We often add -ed to verbs (regular verbs) to make the past simple. We often watch a film on Saturday. ⇒ We watched a film last Saturday. I live in Barcelona. ⇒ I lived in Barcelona in the 90s.",
      "analogy": "",
      "real_world_use": "",
      "memory_hook": "",
      "icon": "🕐",
      "rules": [
        {
          "title": "Spelling of regular verbs",
          "formula": "",
          "explanation": "",
          "memory_hook": "",
          "is_exception": false,
          "order": 1,
          "examples": []
        },
        {
          "title": "When do we double the consonant?",
          "formula": "",
          "explanation": "reFER ⇒ referred, preFER ⇒ preferred, reGRET ⇒ regretted",
          "memory_hook": "",
          "is_exception": false,
          "order": 2,
          "examples": [
            {
              "sentence": "We double the consonant when the verb ends in consonant + vowel + consonant. This is always true when the verb is one syllable.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "stop ⇒ stopped, plan ⇒ planned, shop ⇒ shopped, rob ⇒ robbed.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "When the verb is two syllables, we only double the consonant when the STRESS is in the last syllable.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "But we do NOT double the consonant when the STRESS is NOT in the last syllable.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "VIsit ⇒ visited, ANswer ⇒ answered.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
