            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "A1",
      "title": "Past simple negatives and questions",
      "slug": "a1-past-simple-negatives-and-questions",
      "order": 17,
      "chapter": "Past tenses",
      "description": "We use did and didn’t to make negatives, questions and short answers in past simple.",
      "analogy": "",
      "real_world_use": "",
      "memory_hook": "",
      "icon": "🕐",
      "rules": [
        {
          "title": "Word order in questions",
          "formula": "",
          "explanation": "",
          "memory_hook": "",
          "is_exception": false,
          "order": 1,
          "examples": [
            {
              "sentence": "Remember that the word order in questions is QWASI: (Question Word), Auxiliary (did), Subject, Infinitive.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Infinitive without to",
          "formula": "Did you go to the concert?",
          "explanation": "",
          "memory_hook": "",
          "is_exception": false,
          "order": 2,
          "examples": [
            {
              "sentence": "We use did or didn’t with the bare infinitive of the main verb (= infinitive without to).",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "I didn’t work yesterday.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "I didn’t didn’t worked yesterday.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "Did you went to the concert?",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Don’t use did in positive sentences",
          "formula": "",
          "explanation": "",
          "memory_hook": "",
          "is_exception": false,
          "order": 3,
          "examples": [
            {
              "sentence": "We use did or didn’t in negatives, questions and short answers, but NOT in positive sentences.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "We stayed home yesterday.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "We did stay home yesterday.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "I went out last night.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "I did go out last night.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Did or was/were?",
          "formula": "Did you do your homework?",
          "explanation": "",
          "memory_hook": "",
          "is_exception": false,
          "order": 4,
          "examples": [
            {
              "sentence": "We use did and didn’t (NOT was/wasn’t or were/weren’t) as the auxiliary verb in negatives and questions in past simple.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "We didn’t eat at 6.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "We weren’t eat at 6.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "Were you do your homework?",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "We do NOT use did or didn’t in past simple negatives or questions when the main verb is be.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "They weren’t happy.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "They didn’t be happy.",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "Was he at home?",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            },
            {
              "sentence": "Did he be at home?",
              "translation": "",
              "context": "",
              "highlight": ""
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "A1",
      "title": "Will: Form",
      "slug": "a1-will-form",
      "order": 18,
      "chapter": "Future",
      "description": "Will is an auxiliary verb. This means that: We use will + infinitive: I‘ll be (or will be) at home next Saturday. Will has a negative form: I won’t be (or will not be) at home next Saturday. We put will before the subject in questions: Will you be at home next Saturday? We use will in short answers: Yes, I will. / No, I won’t (or No, I will not).",
      "analogy": "",
      "real_world_use": "",
      "memory_hook": "",
      "icon": "📚",
      "rules": []
    },
    {
      "level": "A1",
      "title": "Will: Use",
      "slug": "a1-will-use",
      "order": 19,
      "chapter": "Future",
      "description": "We use will to talk about things that we think will happen in the future. He will love your new coat. They won’t win this match. 🔍 Note that it’s common to use will with the expressions I think, I don’t think, I hope, etc., or also with I’m sure, I’m not sure, perhaps, etc. I hope they will arrive soon. I don’t think they‘ll win. I’m sure you‘ll be fine. Perhaps I‘ll be late. We use will for promises or refusals. I will lend her the money. I won’t help you. We use will when we make decisions at the moment of speaking (instant decisions). A: There’s no milk in the fridge. B: I’ll go to the shop to buy some more. A: This box is very heavy. B: Don’t worry. I’ll help you.",
      "analogy": "",
      "real_world_use": "",
      "memory_hook": "",
      "icon": "📚",
      "rules": []
    },
    {
      "level": "A1",
      "title": "Shall I…? Shall we…?",
      "slug": "a1-shall-i-shall-we",
      "order": 20,
      "chapter": "Future",
      "description": "We use Shall I…? or I’ll when we offer to do things for other people. Shall I make some coffee? (=Do you want me to make coffee?) I‘ll make some coffee. We use Shall we…? to suggest doing something. Shall we go to the cinema? (=Do you want to go to the cinema?)",
      "analogy": "",
      "real_world_use": "",
      "memory_hook": "",
      "icon": "📚",
      "rules": []
    },
